Part I - (Loan Data from Prosper )¶

by (Sameera Najjar)¶

The dataset contains loan data from Prosper, a peer-to-peer lending platform, with 113,937 loans and 81 variables. These variables include details like loan amount, borrower rate, loan status, borrower income, and more. The data can be used to analyze various factors related to loan performance and borrower characteristics.¶

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset has 113,937 entries and 81 columns. It includes a mix of numeric, categorical, and date variables. Some columns have missing values, such as CreditGrade and ClosedDate.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest could be LoanStatus, BorrowerAPR, and BorrowerRate, as these directly relate to loan performance and cost to the borrower.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Features like CreditGrade, ProsperRating (Alpha), ProsperScore, EmploymentStatus, DebtToIncomeRatio, and BorrowerState are likely to influence LoanStatus and borrower rates.

Univariate Exploration¶

1. Distribution of LoanStatus¶

I start by looking at the distribution of the LoanStatus, which indicates the current status of the loans.¶

In [6]:
# Defining the order of LoanStatus
loan_status_order = [
    'Current', 'Completed', 'FinalPaymentInProgress',
    'Past Due (1-15 days)', 'Past Due (16-30 days)', 'Past Due (31-60 days)', 
    'Past Due (61-90 days)', 'Past Due (91-120 days)', 'Past Due (>120 days)', 
    'Chargedoff', 'Defaulted'
]
In [7]:
# Converting LoanStatus to a categorical variable with the specified order
loan_data['LoanStatus'] = pd.Categorical(loan_data['LoanStatus'], categories=loan_status_order, ordered=True)
In [8]:
# Plotting the distribution of LoanStatus
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
sns.countplot(data=loan_data, x='LoanStatus', order=loan_status_order, palette='viridis')
plt.title('Distribution of Loan Status')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.xlabel('Loan Status')
Out[8]:
Text(0.5, 0, 'Loan Status')

Observations:¶

The most common loan statuses are "Current" and "Completed."¶

There are also a significant number of loans that are "Chargedoff," indicating loans that have defaulted.¶

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The Distribution of the LoanStatus chart illustrates that most loans are "Current" or have been completed, whereas a non-trivial amount has defaulted ("Chargedoff").

The BorrowerAPR has a right skew few loans having very high APRs. At this point, you do not have to transform any of these but the next level analysis that would be involving all these features will need outliers handling.

ProsperRating (Alpha) distribution centered around mid-level ratings that would show both high-risk and low-risk borrowers.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

The BorrowerAPR distribution leaves open some ex-outlier possibilities. This however did not performed any operation till yet in this stage. As a part of bivariate or multivarite analysis, we might have to treat outliers in the raw data itself through transformations.

Observations:¶

There is a general tendency for the debt-to-income ratio to rise in tandem with an increase in the loan original amount. This implies that debt-to-income ratios are typically greater among borrowers who have taken out larger loans.¶
A debt-to-income ratio of less than six indicates that most loans are in good standing (Completed, Current, or Past Due—within one to fifteen days).¶
Debt-to-income ratios more than six indicate a higher risk of default or past due amounts on loans.¶
The fact that there is a large amount of overlap among the various loan statuses suggests that loan performance cannot be strongly predicted by the debt-to-income ratio on its own. It's possible that other elements including the borrower's income, work status, and credit history are also significant.¶

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

There is a strong relationship between BorrowerAPR and ProsperRating (Alpha), indicating that higher-rated borrowers get better loan rates. The LoanStatus varies significantly with EmploymentStatus, where unemployed or self-employed borrowers are more likely to have loans that are "Chargedoff." The DebtToIncomeRatio is higher for loans that default, suggesting a key risk factor.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

The employment status of a borrower seems to have a strong impact on the likelihood of loan default. Borrower income relative to their debt load (DebtToIncomeRatio) is another critical factor influencing loan performance.

Observation¶

The relationship between borrower APRs, loan statuses, and credit ratings is clearly depicted by the facet plot. It draws attention to how different creditworthiness levels have different loan terms, and how these variations affect the results of loans. The graphic also demonstrates how loan status affects the annual percentage rate (APR) even when a borrower is in the same credit rating group. This emphasizes how crucial financial conduct and credit rating are to the evaluation of loan risk.¶

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

LoanStatus and ProsperRating (Alpha): These two factors interact powerfully to affect the BorrowerAPR. Lower APRs are linked to higher ratings and "good" loan statuses (finished, current). DebtToIncomeRatio: This characteristic repeatedly demonstrated that default rates were higher for borrowers with higher debt loads in relation to their income, particularly for those with lower credit scores. LoanOriginalAmount: Higher-rated borrowers typically receive larger loans at lower annual percentage rates (APRs), indicating that they are viewed as more reliable even for greater amounts.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Interaction between ProsperRating (Alpha) and LoanStatus: Even among borrowers with good ratings, those whose loans were charged off had somewhat higher annual percentage rates (APRs). This suggests that even small increases in risk (as judged by lenders) can have a big influence on loan terms. Impact of Debt-to-Income Ratio: The impact of the debt-to-income ratio was more noticeable for borrowers with worse ratings, which may indicate that they are subject to more scrutiny or have less wiggle room when it comes to loan terms.

Conclusions¶

Significant relationships between credit ratings, loan statuses, and financial measures including APR and debt-to-income ratio were found through this multivariate investigation. The results underline the importance of credit rating in dictating loan terms and conditions, but they also show the complex ways in which financial burdenssuch as debt-to-income ratiosaffect lending behavior and risk. These revelations may be vital for lenders evaluating risk as well as for customers comprehending how their credit histories affect the cost and accessibility of loans.

Summary of Findings¶

Univariate Exploration¶

  • Borrower APR Distribution:

    • The distribution of Borrower APR is right-skewed, with most values clustered between 0.1 and 0.4.
    • A significant spike was observed at an APR around 0.36, suggesting a common rate among many borrowers.

  • Prosper Rating (Alpha) Distribution:

    • The most common ratings were C, B, and A, indicating a large proportion of borrowers had mid-range credit ratings.
    • The least common ratings were AA and HR, representing the highest and lowest creditworthiness, respectively.

Bivariate Exploration¶

  • Borrower APR vs. Prosper Rating (Alpha):

    • Borrower APR decreases as Prosper Rating improves. AA rated borrowers have the lowest APRs, while HR rated borrowers have the highest.

  • Debt-to-Income Ratio vs. Loan Status:

    • Borrowers with higher Debt-to-Income Ratios are more likely to have loans that are "Chargedoff" or "Defaulted", indicating higher financial risk.

Multivariate Exploration¶

  • Borrower APR, Prosper Rating (Alpha), and Loan Status:

    • Even among high-rated borrowers (AA, A), those whose loans were charged off had slightly higher APRs compared to those whose loans are current or completed.

  • Debt-to-Income Ratio, Prosper Rating (Alpha), and Loan Status:

    • Higher Debt-to-Income Ratios were more prevalent among lower-rated borrowers (D, E, HR), especially for loans that were eventually "Chargedoff."

  • Loan Amount, Borrower APR, and Prosper Rating (Alpha):

    • Larger loan amounts are generally associated with lower APRs, particularly for high-rated borrowers, indicating better loan terms for those perceived as lower risk.
